b'"I didn\xe2\x80\x99t start my business with a lot of money. I had one credit card, one contract and one retainer, but I also had a contingency plan. My advice for someone looking to start their own business is to know how to do every aspect of your business. I\xe2\x80\x99ve been a project architect, project manager, I\xe2\x80\x99ve done the accounting, and been a designer. When we first started out I would go out on Friday afternoons and collect the money. In the early days I would do everything so I could afford to bring people on later. You should know every aspect of what is needed to get that business done and be willing to do it. Passion is the other key. There are going to be times you\xe2\x80\x99re exhausted and don\xe2\x80\x99t know what to do, but the passion will keep you going."\n\nRainy Hamilton is the Founder and CEO of Hamilton Anderson Associates, an MGM Resorts partner. We\xe2\x80\x99re proud to share Rainy\xe2\x80\x99s story as we strive to focus on #WhatMatters. We invite you to learn more about Hamilton Anderson Associates at @haadetroit.'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cI grew up in the bay area in Foster City, CA. My Dad passed away when I was in the 6th grade and my Mom insisted on keeping me busy with sports and church. I had to grow up fast and in a progressive culture where diversity was the norm. Those ideals impacted and shaped me early on. I had a situation in high school where a locker room fight over music put me in a situation to lead. When the fight erupted, the coach demanded more of me saying, \xe2\x80\x98I need you to fix this, you\xe2\x80\x99re a Senior, a Captain.\xe2\x80\x99 So, I gathered the team which was a mix of Latino, Asian, African American, and Caucasian football teammates and had a DJ friend join-in and we created mixtapes with Rock, Reggae, R&B...all genres. The reason I bring up that story\xe2\x80\x94it taught me an appreciation of diverse thoughts and different cultural points of view.\n\nMy Mom always instilled in me that I could be a leader and I didn\xe2\x80\x99t necessarily see it at the time, but it became a lifelong expectation\xe2\x80\x94I played football at UNLV and in the NFL, and that prepared me to live my truth where coaches and co-workers empowered me to bring teammates from diverse backgrounds together.\xe2\x80\x9d Tony Gladney is VP of Community Engagement for MGM Resorts International.  Today and throughout #BlackHistoryMonth, Tony is focused on #WhatMatters.'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cI\xe2\x80\x99m the youngest of 10 children, born and raised in rural Mississippi. My parents were farmers who transitioned to city jobs when farming became too expensive. I remember harvesting crops as a child and appreciating everything my parents did for us. Growing up Dad taught me to live by the golden rule; treating everyone how he/she wanted to be treated.

Years later while working at Pepsi, part of my job was setting up donations to Three Square. One day when dropping off donations, the COO of Three Square asked if I had ever thought of doing something more worthwhile in my life. I was taken aback but agreed to meet with the CEO of Three Square who offered me a job.

After my first 6 months on the job I knew I had made the right decision\xe2\x80\x94I had a conversation with my Mom who said, \xe2\x80\x98you know, when Dad was farming, he gave away half the food he produced to the local community in need.\xe2\x80\x99 I cried in that moment\xe2\x80\xa6I had no idea. My life flashed full circle with the realization\xe2\x80\x94I am doing exactly as he did to support my local community\xe2\x80\xa6on my hardest day the example my Dad set is my driving force.\xe2\x80\x9d Maurice (Reese) Johnson is Director of Operations for MGM Resorts community partner @ThreeSquareLV Food Bank serving Southern Nevada.  Every day and throughout #BlackHistoryMonth, Reese is focused on #WhatMatters.'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cMy father was diagnosed with cancer when I was in the eighth grade and being the eldest of three immediately shifted my responsibilities to help my family. During my freshman year of high school my Dad passed away and it jolted me\xe2\x80\x94I was a Daddy\xe2\x80\x99s girl, spending a lot of time with him and it took me a long time to adjust. I started hanging with the wrong crowd, grades went down, depressed\xe2\x80\xa6a lot going on. However, my introduction to basketball kept me busy and my love of the game began to grow. That love triggered fond, youthful memories of watching Laker games with my Dad. Playing ball soon became my path and I committed to getting better. Hard work led me to sign a letter of intent at the school of my dreams, UNC at Chapel Hill, but Furman University was closer to home and was exactly what I needed. I graduated Furman and flew off to Europe, playing pro for 3 years\xe2\x80\x94then year-round for 7 years in the WNBA and 5 different countries including Spain, France, Italy, Greece, and Korea\xe2\x80\x94I absolutely loved the opportunity to see different worlds, learn new languages and cultures\xe2\x80\xa6my mindset today is shaped by my diverse experiences.\n\nMy African-American history has also shaped me and I relate most to the real life experiences of those in my life who overcame struggles to find success\xe2\x80\x94be it athletes, lawyers, doctors, teachers, even peers younger than me\xe2\x80\x94everybody is motivated differently and for me, I am inspired to be the best version of myself through witnessing heroes of mine, such as Kobe Bryant, beat odds to accomplish big goals. Kobe\xe2\x80\x99s #MambaMentality lends to everyday life\xe2\x80\xa6most people underestimate the hard work required for success; they don\xe2\x80\x99t know how many times you were told \xe2\x80\x98no,\xe2\x80\x99 the number of times you failed. Kobe\xe2\x80\x99s mindset and support for the WNBA inspired so many young girls through the example he set\xe2\x80\xa6his story will continue to inspire future generations of both men and women in sport and life.\xe2\x80\x9d Rushia Brown leads local community development for our @lvaces through the \xe2\x80\x9cLace-Up\xe2\x80\x9d program that empowers young girls to live well-rounded lives through education, sport and nutrition. Every day and throughout #BlackHistoryMonth, Rushia is focused on #whatmatters'

b"\xe2\x80\x9cOver 12-years ago, I attended the company\xe2\x80\x99s new diversity leadership program, but was reluctant to go\xe2\x80\xa6 I wasn\xe2\x80\x99t going to learn anything new from these guys, I\xe2\x80\x99ve been working in construction for so many years and was set in my ways. However, I was wrong, I came out with a new outlook on life, a new concept of myself. And soon after, the organization Special Spaces was in attendance at one of our Carpenters Union meeting to ask our leaders for volunteers to create a bedroom for a young child with cancer. I stepped forward. 
The first bedroom we did was for a little girl, she was about 4 years old. We decided to create a mermaid-inspired bedroom since she loved The Little Mermaid. After we finished the room that day, her parents brought her to see it. The Father and Mother were crying, overwhelmed with joy\xe2\x80\xa6this was the first time I worked to help a child with cancer and to witness a family struggling to keep their child alive and safe, and doing the best they can. And at that moment the mother wanted to say a prayer; as a Hawaiian we say \xe2\x80\x98Pule\xe2\x80\x99 (to pray for blessing). As I left their home that day, all of the volunteers (who I thought were hardened or tough) were teary-eyed and asked, \xe2\x80\x98when is the next one, when is the next one?\xe2\x80\x99 So, we continued on making Special Spaces for kids. And today, that 4-year old girl is still alive and doing well; I still keep in-touch with the family...the prayers and 'Ohana' of that moment will always be with me.

For Hawaiians, \xe2\x80\x98Ohana\xe2\x80\x99 means family and it\xe2\x80\x99s so important to me\xe2\x80\xa6and not only to me but everybody really\xe2\x80\xa6it\xe2\x80\x99s the reason why we are here every day to work\xe2\x80\x94for your kids, your family.\xe2\x80\x9d A selfless volunteer, Hiro Kajiyama, is focused on #WhatMatters.\xc2\xa0We are proud to share MGM union carpenter and Chapter Director of Special Spaces, Hiroshi Kajiyama\xe2\x80\x99s story of helping those in need through his ongoing volunteerism."
